The show runs January 12-February 9 with an artist reception on Friday, January 14 5-7 p.m. The reception is free and open to the public. <p>This collection of new work addresses individual and common identity and draws on a universal understanding of facial expressions, body language and movement. Each painting is an exploration of how expressions of joy, grief, celebration, frustration, happiness, anger spill out of our physical being, coloring our consciousness.</p><p>Theresa Yantosca's visual art includes graphic design and performance installations for organizations such as Moving People Dance Theatre, Flash in the Pan Produkshins and Bao Bao Festival. This concert by one of the world&#8217;s most renowned Yiddish performers highlights the history of Yiddish behind the &#8220;iron curtain&#8221; in East Germany and asks why would a Communist state be interested in Yiddish at all. The evening&#8217;s repertoire includes some popular favorites like Never Say (Zog nisht keynmol) but also includes some more haunting melodies that made up the canon of East German Yiddish song. CU's Week of Jewish Culture incorporates the theme of Movers: Do You Speak Jewish? this year with authors, scholars and artists from around the world. This annual series is dedicated to the exploration of 3500 years of Jewish culture, including its current, most cutting-edge manifestations! In systems that exhibit self-organizing properties, simple objects interact in simple ways to produce complex structures or emergent behaviors. Examples of natural self-organizing systems abound on all scales, from the microscopic to the cosmologic. In biology, nature uses self-organization to great effect. In certain circumstances, cells self-organize into organisms and organisms self-organize into colonies, flocks, or societies. Despite its importance, self-organization is poorly understood.<br /><br />In this talk, he will provide recent advances in self-organizing systems research, with a concentration on mathematical models and theoretical tools used to aid in understanding self-organizing systems, and present related experimental work from the fields of molecular biology and robotics.</td></tr></table> Thu, 13 Jan 2011 22:30:00 GMT 01/13/2011 CAS Event: Godzilla (1954) Film Screening (1/13/2011) http://events.colorado.edu/EventList.aspx?view=EventDetails&eventidn=5199&information_id=20950&type=&rss=rss <table cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td valign="top"><img src="http://events.colorado.edu/displaymedia.aspx?whatToDo=picture&thumbnail=thumbnail&id=4387" border="0" alt="Godzilla" /></td><td valign="top"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td style="padding-bottom:1px;"><b>Start Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td style="padding-bottom:1px;">1/13/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>Start Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>5:00 PM</td></tr><tr><td><b>End Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>1/13/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>End Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>6:30 PM</td></tr></table><br />Main Campus - And why, despite Godzilla’s destructiveness, do we still love him? Where does Hello Kitty come into this picture and why has she been so important in talking about popular culture and national identity? “From Godzilla to Hello Kitty” will explore the deeper meanings behind two globally famous cultural icons—Godzilla and Hello Kitty—that speak to us about postwar Japan, trauma, and the still unresolved issue of war responsibility. Professor Norihiro Kato (Waseda University) is one of Japan’s most important and controversial Japanese literary and cultural critics. He has published more than thirty books on topics that encompass history, film and visual culture, cultural studies, economics, and political science. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region.</td></tr></table> Fri, 21 Jan 2011 17:00:00 GMT 01/21/2011 Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift (1/21/2011) http://events.colorado.edu/EventList.aspx?view=EventDetails&eventidn=5209&information_id=21013&type=&rss=rss <table cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td valign="top"><img src="http://events.colorado.edu/displaymedia.aspx?whatToDo=picture&thumbnail=thumbnail&id=4409" border="0" alt="Andy Warhol 'Pele', 1977" /></td><td valign="top"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td style="padding-bottom:1px;"><b>Start Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td style="padding-bottom:1px;">1/21/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>Start Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>10:00 AM</td></tr><tr><td><b>End Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>1/21/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>End Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>5:00 PM</td></tr></table><br />Main Campus - Visual Arts Complex<br />Room: CU Art Museum<br /><br /><div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region.</td></tr></table> Wed, 26 Jan 2011 17:00:00 GMT 01/26/2011 Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift (1/26/2011) http://events.colorado.edu/EventList.aspx?view=EventDetails&eventidn=5209&information_id=21017&type=&rss=rss <table cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td valign="top"><img src="http://events.colorado.edu/displaymedia.aspx?whatToDo=picture&thumbnail=thumbnail&id=4409" border="0" alt="Andy Warhol 'Pele', 1977" /></td><td valign="top"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td style="padding-bottom:1px;"><b>Start Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td style="padding-bottom:1px;">1/26/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>Start Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>10:00 AM</td></tr><tr><td><b>End Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>1/26/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>End Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>5:00 PM</td></tr></table><br />Main Campus - Visual Arts Complex<br />Room: CU Art Museum<br /><br /><div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region.</td></tr></table> Fri, 28 Jan 2011 17:00:00 GMT 01/28/2011 Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift (1/28/2011) http://events.colorado.edu/EventList.aspx?view=EventDetails&eventidn=5209&information_id=21019&type=&rss=rss <table cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td valign="top"><img src="http://events.colorado.edu/displaymedia.aspx?whatToDo=picture&thumbnail=thumbnail&id=4409" border="0" alt="Andy Warhol 'Pele', 1977" /></td><td valign="top"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td style="padding-bottom:1px;"><b>Start Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td style="padding-bottom:1px;">1/28/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>Start Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>10:00 AM</td></tr><tr><td><b>End Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>1/28/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>End Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>5:00 PM</td></tr></table><br />Main Campus - Visual Arts Complex<br />Room: CU Art Museum<br /><br /><div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. font: 12.0px Helvetica">September Sixth is Boulder artist Nathan Wheeler's musical/theatrical memoir and response to the devastating Four Mile Canyon fire. <br /><br /> The hour-long performance will be presented two evenings: 8 p.m. Friday-Saturday, Jan. 28-29 in the ATLAS Black Box, downstairs, lower-level B2, CU-Boulder. <br /><br /> CU music graduate Wheeler explains, &#8220;September Sixth is my reaction to the Four Mile Canyon Fire which started on September 6th, 2010. The fire burned our home to the ground&#8211;home to my grandfather who built the house, my parents, younger brother and me. My grandfather built the house in the 1960s. My mother and her family were raised there. And so were my brother and I. We moved in when I was 6."<br /><br /> The piece uses a combination of found art, sound sculpture, dance, music and video to explore the fire, its aftermath and effect on Wheeler's life. A variety of photos of the site taken by collaborators Michael Theodore, Jeff Ruane, Mark McCoin and as well as Wheeler will be projected on the wall of the ATLAS lobby.<br /><br /> &#8220;The performance will feature myself on electronics, harmonium, voice, guitar and found objects. I will also do live video and dance. Janet Feder (a regular performer with the Boulder Laptop Orchestra) will play prepared guitar and found objects. Mark McCoin will also play found objects. CU masters graduate Curtis Broome will play drums. Luke Iwabuchi and Skye Hughes of CU's dance department will provide movement.<br /><br /> &#8220;The work will mirror the emotions I went through because of the fire&#8211;surprise, anguish and suffering, then acceptance, and finally&#8211;peace, joy and reverence."<br /><br /> Musical genres include a cappella, ambient, drone, noise, post-hardcore rock, and electronica. Live video accompanies most of the performance. Dance includes contact improvisation.<br /><br /> The show is free and open to the public. <br /><strong>Reservations are recommended. </strong>Reserve your seat here: http://septsixth.eventbrite.com/<br /><br /> Note: The show will have moments of loud sustained sounds&#8211;earplugs will be provided at the door.</p> <p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; font: The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region.</td></tr></table> Sat, 29 Jan 2011 19:00:00 GMT 01/29/2011 Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift (1/29/2011) http://events.colorado.edu/EventList.aspx?view=EventDetails&eventidn=5209&information_id=21020&type=&rss=rss <table cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td valign="top"><img src="http://events.colorado.edu/displaymedia.aspx?whatToDo=picture&thumbnail=thumbnail&id=4409" border="0" alt="Andy Warhol 'Pele', 1977" /></td><td valign="top"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td style="padding-bottom:1px;"><b>Start Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td style="padding-bottom:1px;">1/29/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>Start Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>12:00 PM</td></tr><tr><td><b>End Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>1/29/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>End Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>4:00 PM</td></tr></table><br />Main Campus - Visual Arts Complex<br />Room: CU Art Museum<br /><br /><div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The fire burned our home to the ground&#8211;home to my grandfather who built the house, my parents, younger brother and me. My grandfather built the house in the 1960s. My mother and her family were raised there. And so were my brother and I. We moved in when I was 6."<br /><br /> The piece uses a combination of found art, sound sculpture, dance, music and video to explore the fire, its aftermath and effect on Wheeler's life. A variety of photos of the site taken by collaborators Michael Theodore, Jeff Ruane, Mark McCoin and as well as Wheeler will be projected on the wall of the ATLAS lobby.<br /><br /> &#8220;The performance will feature myself on electronics, harmonium, voice, guitar and found objects. I will also do live video and dance. Janet Feder (a regular performer with the Boulder Laptop Orchestra) will play prepared guitar and found objects. Mark McCoin will also play found objects. CU masters graduate Curtis Broome will play drums. Luke Iwabuchi and Skye Hughes of CU's dance department will provide movement.<br /><br /> &#8220;The work will mirror the emotions I went through because of the fire&#8211;surprise, anguish and suffering, then acceptance, and finally&#8211;peace, joy and reverence."<br /><br /> Musical genres include a cappella, ambient, drone, noise, post-hardcore rock, and electronica. Live video accompanies most of the performance. Dance includes contact improvisation.<br /><br /> The show is free and open to the public. <br /><strong>Reservations are recommended. </strong>Reserve your seat here: http://septsixth.eventbrite.com/<br /><br /> Note: The show will have moments of loud sustained sounds&#8211;earplugs will be provided at the door.</p> <p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; font: 12.0px Helvetica"> </p></td></tr></table> Sun, 30 Jan 2011 03:00:00 GMT 01/29/2011 The Pillowman (1/30/2011) http://events.colorado.edu/EventList.aspx?view=EventDetails&eventidn=5337&information_id=21747&type=&rss=rss <table cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td valign="top"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td style="padding-bottom:1px;"><b>Start Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td style="padding-bottom:1px;">1/30/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>Start Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>2:00 PM</td></tr><tr><td><b>End Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>1/30/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>End Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>3:00 PM</td></tr></table><div id="id_4d2f3f0f12d319067760188" class="text_exposed_root text_exposed">The University of Colorado Boulder Theatre and Dance Proudly Presents:<br /><br /> THE PILLOWMAN, by Martin McDonagh<br /> Jan 26-30<br /> Directed by LoriLee Wallace<br /><span class="text_exposed_hide">...</span><span class="text_exposed_show"><br /> University of Colorado, Department of Theatre and Dance is proud to present &#8220;The Pillowman&#8221; by Martin McDonagh.<br /><br /> Truth or Fiction? The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region.</td></tr></table> Fri, 4 Feb 2011 17:00:00 GMT 02/04/2011 Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift (2/4/2011) http://events.colorado.edu/EventList.aspx?view=EventDetails&eventidn=5209&information_id=21025&type=&rss=rss <table cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td valign="top"><img src="http://events.colorado.edu/displaymedia.aspx?whatToDo=picture&thumbnail=thumbnail&id=4409" border="0" alt="Andy Warhol 'Pele', 1977" /></td><td valign="top"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td style="padding-bottom:1px;"><b>Start Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td style="padding-bottom:1px;">2/4/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>Start Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>10:00 AM</td></tr><tr><td><b>End Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>2/4/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>End Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>5:00 PM</td></tr></table><br />Main Campus - Visual Arts Complex<br />Room: CU Art Museum<br /><br /><div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region.</td></tr></table> Thu, 24 Feb 2011 17:00:00 GMT 02/24/2011 Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift (2/24/2011) http://events.colorado.edu/EventList.aspx?view=EventDetails&eventidn=5209&information_id=21042&type=&rss=rss <table cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td valign="top"><img src="http://events.colorado.edu/displaymedia.aspx?whatToDo=picture&thumbnail=thumbnail&id=4409" border="0" alt="Andy Warhol 'Pele', 1977" /></td><td valign="top"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td style="padding-bottom:1px;"><b>Start Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td style="padding-bottom:1px;">2/24/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>Start Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>10:00 AM</td></tr><tr><td><b>End Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>2/24/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>End Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>5:00 PM</td></tr></table><br />Main Campus - Visual Arts Complex<br />Room: CU Art Museum<br /><br /><div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region.</td></tr></table> Mon, 28 Feb 2011 17:00:00 GMT 02/28/2011 Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift (2/28/2011) http://events.colorado.edu/EventList.aspx?view=EventDetails&eventidn=5209&information_id=21045&type=&rss=rss <table cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td valign="top"><img src="http://events.colorado.edu/displaymedia.aspx?whatToDo=picture&thumbnail=thumbnail&id=4409" border="0" alt="Andy Warhol 'Pele', 1977" /></td><td valign="top"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td style="padding-bottom:1px;"><b>Start Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td style="padding-bottom:1px;">2/28/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>Start Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>10:00 AM</td></tr><tr><td><b>End Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>2/28/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>End Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>5:00 PM</td></tr></table><br />Main Campus - Visual Arts Complex<br />Room: CU Art Museum<br /><br /><div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region.</td></tr></table> Sat, 5 Mar 2011 19:00:00 GMT 03/05/2011 Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift (3/5/2011) http://events.colorado.edu/EventList.aspx?view=EventDetails&eventidn=5209&information_id=21050&type=&rss=rss <table cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td valign="top"><img src="http://events.colorado.edu/displaymedia.aspx?whatToDo=picture&thumbnail=thumbnail&id=4409" border="0" alt="Andy Warhol 'Pele', 1977" /></td><td valign="top"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td style="padding-bottom:1px;"><b>Start Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td style="padding-bottom:1px;">3/5/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>Start Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>12:00 PM</td></tr><tr><td><b>End Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>3/5/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>End Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>4:00 PM</td></tr></table><br />Main Campus - Visual Arts Complex<br />Room: CU Art Museum<br /><br /><div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. As an international figure, he was offered haven from the horrors that were sure to follow by numerous governments and agencies, yet Picasso chose to stay. In this presentation we will explore his reasons for staying in France. Was it an act of patriotism? Was it indifference? Through his works during this time period we will try to uncover his reasons. Imig Music<br />Room: Chamber Hall (C199)<br /><br />Pianist Nadia Shpachenko has performed extensively in solo and chamber music recitals and with orchestras in North America and Europe in venues such as Carnegie Hall in New York, Concertgebouw in Amsterdam, and the Los Angeles County Museum of Art. Dr. Shpachenko is also touring a series of lecture-recitals exploring the relations between modern art and modern music, including one on Unorthodox Use of Piano by 20th Century American Composers and one commissioned by the Phillips Collection in Washington, DC to accompany its Modigliani exhibit.<br />&#160;<br />Born in Ukraine, Dr. Shpachenko completed her DMA and MM degrees at the University of Southern California, where she was awarded the title of Outstanding Graduate. Her principal teachers have included such distinguished musicians as John Perry, Victor Rosenbaum, and Victor Derevianko. Winner of numerous international piano competitions, she performed at the International Holland Music Sessions, Aspen, Cliburn, Manchester, Orford, Sarasota, Music Academy of the West, Tel-Hai, and Saluzzo International Music Festivals.<br />&#160;<br />Dr. Shpachenko is currently Assistant Professor of Music at the California State Polytechnic University, Pomona. In addition, she has recently served as visiting faculty at Pomona College, guest lecturer at the California Institute of the Arts, and Artist in Residence at the University of Nevada, Las Vegas. A shared history of baseball and a belief in the American dream. This class will link baseball to topics foundational to the American dream: Equality (race), Liberty (women), Prosperity (business and work), Mobility (expansion), and Opportunity (globalization). Professor Tom Zeiler&#8217;s class is for novices and experts alike who wish to study historical trends. This class is not about statistics, games, or the field of dreams but all of these will play a part in our attempt to see what became of the American dream. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region.</td></tr></table> Fri, 15 Apr 2011 16:00:00 GMT 04/15/2011 Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift (4/15/2011) http://events.colorado.edu/EventList.aspx?view=EventDetails&eventidn=5209&information_id=21085&type=&rss=rss <table cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td valign="top"><img src="http://events.colorado.edu/displaymedia.aspx?whatToDo=picture&thumbnail=thumbnail&id=4409" border="0" alt="Andy Warhol 'Pele', 1977" /></td><td valign="top"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td style="padding-bottom:1px;"><b>Start Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td style="padding-bottom:1px;">4/15/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>Start Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>10:00 AM</td></tr><tr><td><b>End Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>4/15/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>End Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>5:00 PM</td></tr></table><br />Main Campus - Visual Arts Complex<br />Room: CU Art Museum<br /><br /><div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region.</td></tr></table> Sat, 25 Jun 2011 18:00:00 GMT 06/25/2011 Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift (6/25/2011) http://events.colorado.edu/EventList.aspx?view=EventDetails&eventidn=5209&information_id=21146&type=&rss=rss <table cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td valign="top"><img src="http://events.colorado.edu/displaymedia.aspx?whatToDo=picture&thumbnail=thumbnail&id=4409" border="0" alt="Andy Warhol 'Pele', 1977" /></td><td valign="top"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td style="padding-bottom:1px;"><b>Start Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td style="padding-bottom:1px;">6/25/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>Start Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>12:00 PM</td></tr><tr><td><b>End Date:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>6/25/2011</td><td>&nbsp;<b>End Time:</b>&nbsp;</td><td>4:00 PM</td></tr></table><br />Main Campus - Visual Arts Complex<br />Room: CU Art Museum<br /><br /><div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program.
